{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473863"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:15:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:15:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11558"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11558"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.04,0.6,0.32,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4187"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80562"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4187"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65853"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"3557"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"5609"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5417"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6223"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26982"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80562"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his mother. He has had a two-day history of vomiting and diarrhoea with reduced oral intake. His mother reports that he has been drowsy and irritable. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears irritable but has normal skin colour. His pulse rate is 128/min, blood pressure 95/50 mmHg, temperature 36.4\u00b0C, respiratory rate 33/min and SpO2 98% on room air. His mucous membranes are dry, eyes are sunken, and he has a central capillary refill time of 4 seconds. His anterior fontanelle appears sunken. His peripheral pulses are normal and extremities are warm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely clinical estimate of fluid loss in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No dehydration - 0%","Mild dehydration - \u003C5%","Moderate dehydration - 5-9%","Severe dehydration - \u226510%","Impending shock"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe grade or degree of dehydration is calculated according to the amount of weight loss as a percentage of the weight prior to the onset of fluid derangement. For example 5% dehydration refers to weight loss equal to 5% of the pre-illness weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn assessing vital signs in the paediatric age group, it is important to refer to the normal ranges for the various age groups. \u003Cstrong\u003EModerate dehydration (5-9%)\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by mildly to moderately abnormal signs including lethargy and irritability, sunken eyes and fontanelles, dry mucous membranes, mildly decreased skin turgor, and prolonged capillary refill time. There may be mild tachycardia, mild tachypnoea, near normal to slightly reduced peripheral pulse volume, normal skin colour, warm extremities, and normal blood pressure. Urine output may be reduced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor his age, this patient is normotensive with mild tachycardia and a mild increase in respiratory rate. A normal central capillary refill time should be \u0026lt;2 seconds, so 4 seconds is prolonged. His peripheral pulses and skin colour are normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMild dehydration (\u0026lt;5%)\u003C/strong\u003E presents with grossly normal signs including an alert and responsive child, normal vital signs, moist mucous membranes, instant skin recoil, and normal capillary refill time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Esevere dehydration (\u226510%)\u003C/strong\u003E, signs are markedly abnormal and may include reduced consciousness, tachycardia, tachypnoea, deep acidotic breathing, hypotension, and pale or mottled skin. Other signs include cool peripheries, weak pulses, deeply sunken eyes and fontanelles, dry mucous membranes, decreased skin turgor, markedly prolonged capillary refill time, and marked oliguria or anuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpending shock\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate description for this patient. The cardinal feature of shock is inadequate tissue perfusion as evidenced by decreased skin temperature, confusion, or oliguria in conjunction with either hypotension or tachycardia. This patient does not have any of these features. In fluid resuscitation, the regimen is calculated based on estimated fluid losses, and grading dehydration as mild, moderate or severe is more universally accepted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Moderate dehydration (5-9%) can present with irritability, mildly deranged vital signs and capillary refill time, sunken eyes and fontanelles, mildly decreased skin turgor but warm extremities, normal skin colour and normal blood pressure.","It is important to relate the values of vital signs in paediatric patients to the reference ranges for the various age groups."],"references":["Clinical Practice Guidelines : Dehydration. [online] 2022 [Accessed 2025 Jan 20] Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Dehydration/","Clinical Practice Guidelines : Acceptable ranges for physiological variables. [online] 2022 [Accessed 2025 Jan 20] Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Normal_Ranges_for_Physiological_Variables/","Daley SF, Avva U. Pediatric Dehydration. [Updated 2024 Jun 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK436022/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65853"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11558"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65853"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-21T16:38:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-21T16:40:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4187"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80562"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap